  <li><strong>Serve at 60-65°F, Not Room Temperature</strong> - Budget Cabernets under $20 often have higher alcohol levels (14-15% ABV) and can taste hot when served too warm. Chill your bottle in the refrigerator for 15-20 minutes before serving to bring out the fruit clarity and soften any harsh edges while maintaining the wine's natural structure.</li>

  <li><strong>Decant Young, Affordable Cabernets for 30-45 Minutes</strong> - Unlike expensive, aged Cabernets that need hours of decanting, the best Cabernet Sauvignon under $20 benefits from brief aeration. Most are 2-4 years old and just need enough time to blow off any reductive notes and integrate alcohol with fruit, making them more approachable immediately.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Larger Bordeaux Glasses to Maximize Aromatics</strong> - Affordable Cabernets often have more restrained aromatics than their premium counterparts. A proper Bordeaux glass with a wide bowl (22-24 oz capacity) concentrates the wine's cassis, cedar, and spice notes, making even a $15 bottle smell and taste more complex than it would in a standard wine glass.</li>

  <li><strong>Buy Current Vintage Releases from Established Producers</strong> - The best value Cabernets under $20 are typically current or recent releases (2020-2022 vintages) from established wineries like Bogle, Columbia Crest, or Hess Select. These producers have consistent winemaking and distribution, ensuring proper storage and quality control that boutique labels can't always guarantee at this price point.</li>

